Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

This soccer database comes from Kaggle and is well suited for data analysis and machine learning. It contains data for soccer matches, players, and teams from several European countries from 2008 to 2016.
-+25,000 matches
-+10,000 players
-11 European Countries with their lead championship
-Seasons 2008 to 2016
-Players and Teams' attributes* sourced from EA Sports' FIFA video game series, including the weekly updates
-Detailed match events (goal types, possession, corner, cross, fouls, cards etc…) for +10,000 matches

Tables
Country
League
Match
Player
Player_Attributes
Team
Team_Attributes

**All tables are linked with each other with ids

Data Wrangling¶

Loading Data from SQL¶

Refrence:https://www.kaggle.com/abhishektripathy/data-analysis-with-sql#List-of-Teams

In [2]:
# Load your data and print out a few lines. Perform operations to inspect data
#   types and look for instances of missing or possibly errant data.
conn = sqlite3.connect('database.sqlite') 
countries = pd .read_sql('SELECT * FROM Country',conn)
leagues = pd.read_sql('SELECT * FROM League JOIN Country ON Country.id = League.country_id',conn)
df_t = pd.read_sql_query ('SELECT * FROM Team', conn)
players=pd.read_sql("""SELECT Player.player_name,
                                 Player.birthday,
                                 Player.height,
                                 Player.weight,
                                 date,
                                 overall_rating,
                                 potential,
                                 preferred_foot,
                                 heading_accuracy,
                                 penalties,
                                 sprint_speed
                       FROM Player_Attributes
                       JOIN Player on Player.player_api_id = Player_Attributes.player_api_id""",conn
                   )
detailed_matches = pd.read_sql("""SELECT Match.id,
                                        Country.name AS country_name, 
                                        League.name AS league_name, 
                                        season,
                                        date,
                                        stage, 
                                        HT.team_long_name AS  home_team,
                                        AT.team_long_name AS away_team,
                                        home_team_goal, 
                                        away_team_goal                                        
                                FROM Match
                                JOIN Country on Country.id = Match.country_id
                                JOIN League on League.id = Match.league_id
                                LEFT JOIN Team AS HT on HT.team_api_id = Match.home_team_api_id
                                LEFT JOIN Team AS AT on AT.team_api_id = Match.away_team_api_id   
                                ORDER by date""",conn)
df_ta =pd.read_sql_query('SELECT * FROM Team_Attributes',conn) 
df=pd.merge(left=df_t , right=df_ta , how='inner',on='team_api_id')

#getting the total goals scored in each match
detailed_matches['Total Goals']=detailed_matches['home_team_goal']+detailed_matches['away_team_goal']

Refrence:https://www.dataquest.io/blog/tutorial-add-column-pandas-dataframe-based-on-if-else-condition/

In [34]:
conditions = [
    (detailed_matches['home_team_goal'] > detailed_matches['away_team_goal']),
    (detailed_matches['home_team_goal'] < detailed_matches['away_team_goal']) ,
    (detailed_matches['home_team_goal'] == detailed_matches['away_team_goal'])
             ]

# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = ['Home', 'Away', 'Draw']
values1 = [detailed_matches['home_team'], detailed_matches['away_team'], 'Draw']

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
detailed_matches['Win'] = np.select(conditions, values)
detailed_matches['Winner'] = np.select(conditions, values1)

In [48]:
def plotting_scatter(df,x,y,title,xl,yl):
    df.plot(x,y,kind='scatter');
    plt.xlabel(xl)
    plt.ylabel(yl)
    plt.title(title)
def Plotting_hist(df,x):
    df.hist(x);
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.title('Distribution of {}'.format(x))

Conclusions¶

1- The most improved team from 2010 to 2016 was found to be Empoli.
2- Spain appears to be the country with most total goals while Switzerland appears to be the lowest.
3- Spain has scored most goals in one season in 2008/2009 while Germany has scored the least in 2014/2015.
4- Home team has more possibilities to win by 46%.
5- Attributes like 'Chance Creation Passing','Chance Creation Crossing','Chance Creation Shooting'and 'Defence Pressure' have positive correlation with number of wins. However,Attributes like 'Build Up Passing' seems to have negative correlation with wins.
6- 75% of players prefer right foot while only 25% prefer the left one.
7- Most players appear to be from 22 to 25 and 28 to 30. 8- Most players appear to be around 185 cm.
9- Most players appear to have weight around 160.
10- The players' rating increases to a certain age then it begins to decrese with the age.
11- Sprint speed and potenial have negative correlantion with age.
12- Also Sprint speed is affected by weight as it decreases as weight increases.
13- Headind accuracy is affected by height as it increase as height increases.
14- The player with the most penalities in 2016 is : Rickie Lambert.

Limitations¶

-This database is based on a sample collected between 2008 and 2016 for some of european teams and players which doesnot represent the full image of the population. This makes the analysis easier but it doesnot give a 100% accurate output but it still gives an indication.
-Some of the data were missing so we must fill them with different methods according the data itself to start our analysis.
-There was some duplicate rows and also multiple data for the same players in the same year in which we dealt with by keeping only the latest entry.
-Maybe data would be better to be collected from the official sites of the leagues rather than depending on some other sites and games like 'Fifa', also the sample may be better if we had data from more leagues,teams,players and matches in more countries and over a larger period of time.
